bly a metonymic occupational name for a shepherd. In Northamptonshire the name attracts excrescent <i>-s</i> already by 1377."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":8,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":43,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Bellers was born in 1216, in Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England, his father, Rafe I de Bellers of Kettleby, was 49 and his mother, Emma de Foleville, was 46. He died in 1273, in Kirby Bellars, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1216–1273":"1216–1273","1198–Male":"1198–Surnud","1204–Male":"1204–Surnud","1207–Male":"1207–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","–1216":"–1216","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","–Femal